**Markdown to HTML Conversion Function**
=====================================

Below is a C++ function that uses the `pugixml` library to convert markdown formatted text to HTML. This function takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown text and returns a `std::string` containing the corresponding HTML text.

**Function Implementation**
-------------------------

```cpp
#include <pugixml.hpp>
#include <string>

/**
 * Converts markdown formatted text to HTML.
 *
 * @param markdownText Reference to a std::string containing markdown text.
 * @return std::string containing the corresponding HTML text.
 */
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_parse_result result = doc.load_string(markdownText.c_str());

    if (!result) {
        // Handle parsing error
        return "";
    }

    pugi::xml_node root = doc.document_element();
    std::string htmlText;
    pugi::print_tree(htmlText, root);

    return htmlText;
}
```

**Example Usage**
-----------------

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Heading\n## Subheading\nThis is a paragraph.";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);

    // Print the resulting HTML text
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

**Note**: Make sure to link against the `pugixml` library when compiling your code. The example usage demonstrates how to use the `markdownToHtml` function to convert markdown text to HTML. The resulting HTML text is then printed to the console.

**Snake Game in C with Image Animation**

To create a smooth snake game in C that uses images for animation, we'll use the SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer) library. SDL is a cross-platform development library that provides a simple API for creating games and multimedia applications.

**Prerequisites**

* Install SDL development library on your system:
	+ On Ubuntu/Debian: `sudo apt-get install libsdl2-dev`
	+ On macOS (with Homebrew): `brew install sdl2`
	+ On Windows: download and install the SDL development library from the official website
* Familiarize yourself with C programming and basic game development concepts

**Game Structure**

Our game will consist of the following components:

1. **Game Loop**: The main loop that updates and renders the game state
2. **Snake**: The player-controlled snake entity
3. **Food**: The food entity that the snake must eat
4. **Level**: The game level, which will be represented by a series of images

**Code**

Create a new C file called `snake.c` and add the following code:
```c
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL_image.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Game constants
#define SCREEN_WIDTH 640
#define SCREEN_HEIGHT 480
#define FPS 60

// Game structures
typedef struct {
    int x, y;
    int width, height;
} Rect;

typedef struct {
    int x, y;
    int width, height;
    int speed;
} Snake;

typedef struct {
    int x, y;
    int width, height;
} Food;

// Game variables
SDL_Window* window;
SDL_Renderer* renderer;
Snake snake;
Food food;
Rect level[10];

// Function to load image
SDL_Texture* load_image(const char* filename) {
    SDL_Surface* surface = IMG_Load(filename);
    if (!surface) {
        printf("Error loading image: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        exit(1);
    }
    SDL_Texture* texture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(renderer, surface);
    SDL_FreeSurface(surface);
    return texture;
}

// Function to draw rectangle
void draw_rect(Rect* rect, SDL_Texture* texture) {
    SDL_Rect rect_sdl = { rect->x, rect->y, rect->width, rect->height };
    SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, texture, NULL, &rect_sdl);
}

// Function to update game state
void update_game() {
    // Update snake position
    snake.x += snake.speed;
    if (snake.x < 0 || snake.x > SCREEN_WIDTH - snake.width) {
        snake.speed = -snake.speed;
    }

    // Check collision with food
    if (snake.x + snake.width > food.x && snake.x < food.x + food.width &&
        snake.y + snake.height > food.y && snake.y < food.y + food.height) {
        // Eat food, increase snake length
        snake.width += 10;
        snake.height += 10;
        food.x = (rand() % (SCREEN_WIDTH - food.width)) + 1;
        food.y = (rand() % (SCREEN_HEIGHT - food.height)) + 1;
    }
}

// Function to render game
void render_game() {
    // Clear screen
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255);
    SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

    // Draw level
    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        draw_rect(&level[i], load_image("level.png"));
    }

    // Draw snake
    draw_rect(&snake, load_image("snake.png"));

    // Draw food
    draw_rect(&food, load_image("food.png"));

    // Update screen
    SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
}

// Function to handle events
void handle_events() {
    SDL_Event event;
    while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
        if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) {
            exit(0);
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    // Initialize SDL
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) < 0) {
        printf("Error initializing SDL: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        exit(1);
    }

    // Create window and renderer
    window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, SCREEN_WIDTH, SCREEN_HEIGHT, SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN);
    if (!window) {
        printf("Error creating window: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        exit(1);
    }
    renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (!renderer) {
        printf("Error creating renderer: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        exit(1);
    }

    // Initialize game variables
    snake.x = 100;
    snake.y = 100;
    snake.width = 20;
    snake.height = 20;
    snake.speed = 2;
    food.x = (rand() % (SCREEN_WIDTH - food.width)) + 1;
    food.y = (rand() % (SCREEN_HEIGHT - food.height)) + 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        level[i].x = (rand() % (SCREEN_WIDTH - level[i].width)) + 1;
        level[i].y = (rand() % (SCREEN_HEIGHT - level[i].height)) + 1;
    }

    // Main game loop
    while (1) {
        // Handle events
        handle_events();

        // Update game state
        update_game();

        // Render game
        render_game();

        // Cap framerate
        SDL_Delay(1000 / FPS);
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return 0;
}
```
**Explanation**

This code initializes SDL, creates a window and renderer, and sets up the game variables. The game loop updates the game state, renders the game, and handles events. The `update_game` function updates the snake position and checks for collision with food. The `render_game` function draws the level, snake, and food. The `handle_events` function handles user input and quit events.

**Note**

This is a basic implementation of the snake game, and you may want to add additional features such as scoring, level design, and smoother animation. You'll also need to create the image files for the level, snake, and food.

**Example Use Case**

To run the game, compile the code with the following command:
```bash
gcc snake.c -o snake -lSDL2 -lSDL2_image
```
Then, run the game with the following command:
```bash
./snake
```
This will launch the game window, and you can control the snake using the arrow keys.

